With a record number of people being displaced from their homes due to conflict, climate change and more, we sat down with the CEO and Founder of @safehaven_va Egette Indelele to discuss her efforts to provide mental health services to refugee and immigrant youth.

Ahead of World Refugee Day on June 20th, Safe Haven wants to hear from you on how this community has positively impacted your life. Follow the hashtag #DecreaseStigmaIncreaseConnectionsForRefugees to learn more!

node.title: World Refugee Day: A Conversation With @egette_tnz

node.text:
The lives of hundreds of millions of children have been upended by coronavirus. With schools closed and coronavirus spreading across the world, hundreds of millions of children are trapped indoors. 
Parents and kids face many challenges as they adjust to working and learning from home. The transition while maintaining physical distance from friends, colleagues, teachers and extended family has placed great strain on kids. Keeping kids focused on their education can provide the reassuring structure and emotional support that will get them through this unprecedented time.

Here, UNICEF's Global Education Chief Robert Jenkins offers 5 tips for parents on how to keep their children learning and help them cope.

node.title: How to Help Kids Cope with Coronavirus

Menstrual hygiene is a real problem in Mauritania because of the lack of sanitation facilities and information — pushing many young girls to drop out of school. But at the UNICEF-supported Dar Naim girls' activity center on the outskirts of Nouakchott, teenage girls and young women learn how to sew reusable cloth sanitary pads.

"I am participating for the first time in the sanitary pad making workshop," says 23-year-old Aliya. "It is very important for us young girls because we don't have access to quality pads, so often we have to manage as we can."

📸: unicefmauritanie

"My dream is to become a pharmacist."

#ForEveryChild, opportunity.

⁠

#ForEveryChild, support.
📸: @unicefafghanistan

Fifty years ago today, George Harrison and Ravi Shankar put on the #ConcertForBangladesh, raising money for emergency relief efforts for the country — which at the time had been suffering from the effects of floods, famine and civil war.

Today, in partnership with UNICEF USA, the George Harrison Fund for UNICEF is keeping the legacy alive.
